---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Multi-Server Deployments"
  description="Deploy to multiple servers and server groups in parallel, with independent SSH connections, locks, and state per host."
  section="features"
>
  <p>
    Shuttle can deploy to any number of servers simultaneously. Hosts are organized into named
    groups, each with its own list of hosts and SSH user. Shuttle dispatches all hosts in parallel
    (up to the configured concurrency limit), and each host has completely independent SSH
    connections, deploy locks, and state files.
  </p>

  <h2>Server groups</h2>
  <p>
    Replace the <code>server:</code> shorthand with a <code>servers:</code> map to define multiple
    groups:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com

servers:
  web:
    hosts:
      - 203.0.113.10
      - 203.0.113.11
      - 203.0.113.12
    user: deploy

  workers:
    hosts:
      - 203.0.113.20
      - 203.0.113.21
    user: deploy

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green
  concurrency: 5          # max hosts deploying in parallel (default: 5)
</code></pre>

  <h2>Parallel execution</h2>
  <p>
    Shuttle flattens all server groups into a single list of hosts, then executes deploys in
    parallel using a semaphore with the configured <code>concurrency</code> limit (default: 5).
    With the example above and <code>concurrency: 5</code>, all 5 hosts deploy simultaneously.
  </p>
  <p>
    Each host runs the full deploy pipeline independently:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>Open SSH connection to the host</li>
    <li>Acquire deploy lock (<code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/.deploy.lock/</code>)</li>
    <li>Ensure accessories are running</li>
    <li>Run pre-deploy hooks</li>
    <li>Execute deploy strategy for each service</li>
    <li>Run post-deploy hooks</li>
    <li>Release deploy lock</li>
    <li>Close SSH connection</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Independent failure isolation</h2>
  <p>
    A failure on one host does not abort deploys on other hosts. All hosts are given the chance to
    complete (or fail). After all parallel tasks finish, Shuttle collects errors and reports them
    together:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">Deploy failed on 1 host(s):
  - 203.0.113.11 (web): Health check failed for "web" on 203.0.113.11
</code></pre>
  <p>
    This means the other 4 hosts in the example above would successfully deploy even if one host
    has an issue. Monitor your deployment state with <code>shuttle status</code> to identify and
    re-deploy the failed host.
  </p>

  <h2>Per-host deploy lock</h2>
  <p>
    Each host has its own deploy lock at <code>/opt/shuttle/&lt;app&gt;/.deploy.lock/</code>. This
    prevents concurrent deploys to the same host (e.g., from two CI jobs running simultaneously).
    If a lock exists, Shuttle shows who holds it:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">Deployment lock already exists for "my-app" on 203.0.113.10
(owner host=203.0.113.10, pid=12345, created_at=2026-03-26T10:00:00Z)
</code></pre>
  <p>
    Force-release a stale lock with <code>shuttle lock release --host 203.0.113.10</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Typical multi-tier setup</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">app: my-app
domain: my-app.example.com

servers:
  web:
    hosts:
      - 10.0.1.10
      - 10.0.1.11
    user: deploy

  workers:
    hosts:
      - 10.0.2.10
    user: deploy

services:
  web:
    command: node server.js
    port: 3000
    healthcheck:
      type: http
      path: /health

  worker:
    command: node worker.js
    replicas: 2

deploy:
  strategy: blue-green
  concurrency: 5
  hooks:
    pre_deploy:
      - php artisan migrate --force
</code></pre>
  <p>
    In this setup, the migration runs once per host. If you want it to run only on one host, use a
    flag file or a conditional command in your pre-deploy hook.
  </p>

  <h2>Single-server shorthand</h2>
  <p>
    For single-server apps, the <code>server:</code> shorthand normalizes to a
    <code>servers: &#123; default: &#123; hosts: [...] &#125; &#125;</code> map internally:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml"># Shorthand (single server)
server:
  host: 203.0.113.10
  user: deploy

# Equivalent expanded form
servers:
  default:
    hosts:
      - 203.0.113.10
    user: deploy
</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
